ce:section.ce:para:
To evaluate the practical applicability of the developed sensor, the intensity of fluorescence emissions of the probe due to diuron in radish, tomato, cucumber and green tea samples was measured using the spectrophotometer and smartphone-assisted color analysis platform. Different diuron concentrations spiked in samples were determined by HPLC and the smartphone-assisted sensing platform and recoveries were also calculated. As displayed in Table 1
                        , low concentrations of diuron (0.46–0.55 μg L−1) were found in some cucumber samples. The spectrophotometric analysis and smartphone-assisted analysis demonstrated that the proposed fluorescent probe produced satisfactory recoveries ranging from 90.5 to 107.3 % and 91.5–105.3 %. The respective RSDs were below 8.0 and 7.0 %. Furthermore, the results obtained from both analysis methods were consistent with the HPLC results (Fig. S6A-S6C). HPLC chromatograms of spiked samples are shown in Fig. S6D. The results revealed that the fluorescent probe coupled with smartphone-assisted color analysis was a highly accurate procedure, reliable and applicable to the determination of diuron in food samples. The two proposed analytical methods of diuron detection were compared to reported methods (Table 2
                        ). Both proposed methods exhibited better sensitivity than reported methods. The LODs were significantly lower than other methods. Recoveries and precision were comparable or better than some other methods. In addition, both methods are cost-effective, whereas chromatographic methods are expensive. In particular, the accuracy and precision of the smartphone-assisted analysis are significant advantages for on-site quantitative detection. The comparison indicated that both proposed methods could determine diuron with good accuracy, reliability, sensitivity and selectivity.
